<subSubSection box="[151,544,1231,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,544,1231,1258]" box="[151,544,1231,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,544,1231,1258]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,544,1231,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">
Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Stephens 1829" authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1829" box="[238,544,1231,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Chimarra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[238,357,1231,1258]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">Chimarra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stephens, J. F." box="[365,544,1231,1257]" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" refId="ref6851" refString="Stephens, J. F. (1829) A Systematic Catalogue of British Insects, Being an Attempt to Arrange All the Hitherto Discovered Indigenous Insects in Accordance with Their Natural Affinities; Containing also the References to Every English Writer on Entomology, and to the Principal Foreign Authors; with All the Published British Genera to the Present Time. Baldwin, London, 388 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / t. 174460" type="book" year="1829">Stephens 1829</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="583" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1303,1402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">
This genus is divided into four subgenera (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1829" box="[636,746,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Chimarra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[636,746,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">Chimarra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik" authorityYear="1997" box="[761,887,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Chimarrita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[761,887,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">Chimarrita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[902,980,1304,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Trichoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Curgia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[902,980,1304,1330]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">Curgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik" authorityYear="2002" box="[1043,1134,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Otarrha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1043,1134,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">Otarrha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the latter three of which, with the exception of a few species of 
<taxonomicName box="[599,677,1340,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Trichoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Curgia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="583" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[599,677,1340,1366]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="583">Curgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are endemic to the Neotropics. Over 256 Neotropical species are distributed among the subgenera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
